observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the concerned officers and employees to:
a. Strictly implement Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and all the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 on the grant and liquidation of cash advances;
b. Review and improve the process of the preparation and approval of payrolls to reduce the number of payrolls and granting of multiple cash advances to the same DO;
c. Stop the practice of designating or assigning the disbursement or pay-out of birthday cash gift incentive for Senior Citizens to Job Order personnel of the Municipality;
d. Comply with the documentary requirements required by COA Circular No. 2023-004, specifically, the issuance of Certification from the Chief Accountant that previous cash advances have been fully liquidated and accounted for in the books; and
e. Increase the fidelity bond of the concerned Disbursing Officer and ensure that she is properly bonded in accordance with Treasury Circular No. 002-2019; otherwise, appoint or designate another DO for the grant of additional cash advances.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Treasurer to:
a. Coordinate with the taxpayers who paid the advance payments to facilitate the issuance of the corresponding AF No. 56;
b. Transfer the remaining balance of advance collections from the bank account immediately to the correct bank accounts after all the concerned taxpayers were properly identified;
c. Issue RPT Receipt or AF No. 56 for all the collections/payments received pertaining to RPT and deposit the same under the bank accounts maintained in the GF and SEF;
d. Evaluate the existing computerized RPT System and recommend the need for replacement or upgrade to improve the efficiency of recording collections; and
Municipal Accountant to:
e. Make the necessary adjusting entries in the books of the Municipality to correct the entries made pertaining to advance payments for RPT; and
f. Record the receipt of RPT from taxpayer with discount for the advanced payment using the following entry: Debit: Cash Local Treasury; Discount on Advance Payment of RPT; Credit: Deferred RPT/SET Income; Due to LGUs.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and other concerned Municipal Officials to:
a. Effectively and judiciously plan the priority development programs, projects and activities to be included in the AIP, considering their feasibility and necessity;
b. Request the Sanggunian to appropriate the proceeds from Share from National Wealth of the Municipality to finance eligible PPAs;
c. Instruct the MPDC, and other concerned Municipal Officials to ensure that PPAs are feasible and procurement-ready; and
d. Prepare and submit the required reports and supporting documents to monitor the utilization of the funds.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to:
a. Send demand letters to the Accountable Officers with unliquidated cash advances;
b. Withhold the salary of those AOs who still failed to liquidate their cash advances without valid reason despite demands;
c. Strictly monitor the liquidation of the cash advances and ensure that all CA are fully liquidated at the end of each year in accordance with COA Circular No. 97-002; and
d. Immediately submit the two (2) unsubmitted DVs to the Office of Disbursement Vouchers (DVs) with respect to Advances to Officers and Employees related to Trainings and Seminars.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor and other concerned Municipal Officials to:
a. Submit written explanation or justification on the necessity of hiring the consultants in such a way that their employment did not create duplication of work already performed by existing agency work force; otherwise, such consultancy fees will be disallowed in audit;
b. Provide or submit the qualifications or special skills of the consultants which made them qualified as “experts in an acknowledged authority in their field of specialization”;
c. Provide the basis in determining the reasonableness of the monthly compensation of the consultants; and
d. Provide the Municipal Accountant of the copy of curriculum vitae of the consultants, Accomplishment Reports or outputs as required under the contract and letter request for payment of each consultant as supporting documents to the disbursement vouchers pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001 as amended by COA Circular No. 2023-004.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the concerned Municipal Officials to:
a. Effectively and judiciously plan the priority development programs, projects and activities to be included in the AIP, considering their feasibility and necessity;
b. Submit further written explanations and justifications on the non-implementation of the priority PPAs funded under the 20 percent DF;
c. Evaluate whether all the PPAs programmed under the continuing appropriations are still viable and ready for implementation, otherwise realign the fund for other projects; and
d. Prepare the AIP with all the necessary information including project implementation timeline and budget for each PPA and ensure procurement and implementation readiness.

a. Inventory Committee to conduct an actual physical count of all PPEs and submit the required RPCPPE in the prescribed template to the Office of the Auditor not later than January 31 of the ensuing year;
b. Municipal Accountant to:
• draw Journal Entry Voucher to drop the semi-expendable properties from the books by debiting the Government Equity and Accumulated Depreciation of the respective PPE and crediting the respective PPE accounts in the General Fund books in the amounts of P246,998.98, P949,059.52 and P1,196,058.50, respectively; and in the Special Education Fund books in the amounts of P131.05, P8,558.95 and P8,690.00, respectively;
• exert efforts to secure the necessary documents to support the undepreciated PPEs by tracing back all available records and prepare thereafter lapsing schedule of PPE to compute the unrecognized depreciation; and
• draw Journal Entry Voucher to record the unrecognized depreciation by debiting Government Equity and crediting the corresponding Accumulated Depreciation by the amount computed in the lapsing schedule of PPE;
c. Municipal General Services Officer to ensure that all of the semi-expendable properties which are still existing are covered by ICS for monitoring and control purposes.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the:
a. stop the practice of charging regular expenditures against the LDF, otherwise, the transactions shall be suspended/disallowed in audit;
b. appropriate and utilize the LDF for PPAs that contribute to the attainment of socio-economic and environmental outcomes;
c. strictly implement the development projects included in the Annual Development Plan to fully optimize the utilization of the LDF and achieve the desirable socio-economic and environmental outcomes.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer/GSO and the Municipal Accountant to:

Review the records pertaining to the PPE account to determine the cause/s of the discrepancy noted in their records as reconciling items and thereafter to make the necessary adjustments/ corrections;

Municipal Accountant to reclassify, upon receipt of a copy of the approved Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), the obsolete/unserviceable properties from PPE Account to Other Assets Account and to record in the books of the Municipality the carnapped municipal vehicle charge against the concerned accountable officer.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the Municipal Mayor require the:

Municipal Assessor to gather the necessary documents for the titling of the donated six parcels of land in the name of the Municipality and to provide both the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer with the appraisal report on the current market value of each the said donated parcel land;

Municipal General Services Officer to record in the Real Estate Property Card the donated three parcels of land base on the appraisal report provided by the Municipal Assessor;

Municipal Accountant to record in the books of the Municipality the donated three parcels of land base on the appraisal report provided by the Municipal Assessor; and

Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer to reconcile the discrepancy of P1,840,966.86 between their records on the land owned by the Municipality.
